The article is a transcript of remarks made by President Trump at a dinner before the National Day of Prayer. The President thanked First Lady Melania for hosting the event and acknowledged the presence of Vice President Mike Pence and Second Lady Karen Pence. He also mentioned the presence of leaders from various faiths, including Christians, Muslims, Jews, Sikhs, and Hindus, and emphasized the importance of protecting religious freedom.

The President expressed condolences for recent acts of violence against people of different faiths, including the shooting at the Chabad of Poway synagogue in California, the bombings in Sri Lanka, the burning of historically black churches in Louisiana, and the shooting at the Tree of Life synagogue in Pittsburgh. He called for an end to violence and terrorism against people of all faiths.

President Trump also mentioned the confirmation of the 100th federal judge by the Senate, highlighting his administration's efforts to reshape the judiciary. He emphasized the importance of religious faith, especially during the Easter, Passover, and Ramadan seasons, and the role it plays in shaping individuals and the nation. The President highlighted America's history as a nation of faith and invoked the words "Praise be to God" inscribed on the Washington Monument.

He also mentioned the resurgence of saying "Merry Christmas" and expressed gratitude for the nation's blessings, while asking for continued protection and blessings for religious believers and people of goodwill worldwide. The President concluded by thanking the attendees and expressing anticipation for the National Day of Prayer.